definitions.definition: Containing the maximum possible amount that can fit in the space available.
examples: The jugs were full to the point of overflowing.
Our book gives full treatment to the subject of angling.

subdefinitions.definition: Surjective as a map of morphisms
labels: of a functor between locally small categories
subdefinitions.label_groups: category theory , of a functor between locally small categories

subdefinitions.definition: Including all morphisms. Formally : Such that for every pairs of objects (X, Y) in S, the hom-sets Hom S ⁡ ( X , Y ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {Hom} _{S}(X,Y)} and Hom C ⁡ ( X , Y ) {\displaystyle \operatorname {Hom} _{C}(X,Y)} are equal.
labels: of a subcategory S of C
subdefinitions.label_groups: category theory , of a subcategory S of C

examples: She had tattoos the full length of her arms.   He was prosecuted to the full extent of the law.

definitions.definition: Completely empowered , authorized or qualified (in some role); not limited .
Having eaten to satisfaction , having a "full" stomach; replete .
examples: "I'm full ," he said, pushing back from the table.
This movie doesn't make sense; it's full of plot holes.
I prefer my pizzas full of toppings.
Hang on - my hands are full ; just let me put these down.
definitions.label_groups: informal , of hands , chiefly in the plural

examples: full lips; a full face; a full figure

definitions.definition: Of a size that is ample, wide, or having ample folds or pleats to be comfortable .
examples: a full pleated skirt; She needed her full clothing during her pregnancy.

definitions.definition: Having the mind filled with ideas; stocked with knowledge; stored with information.
Having the attention, thoughts, etc., absorbed in any matter, and the feelings more or less excited by it.
examples: She's full of her latest project.

definitions.definition: Said of the three cards of the same rank in a full house .
examples: I'll beat him with my kings full !
